ce:section.ce:para:
Lanthanide metal–organic frameworks (Ln-MOFs) are attractive because of their excellent optical properties derived from an “antenna effect” and the well-defined porosity of MOF surfaces. It is promising that Ln-MOFs can work as good candidates for CL emission. In this work, the main aim is constructing Ln-MOFs (Ln = Ce, Gd, Ho) by ultrasonic synthesis and applying them in CL process (Fig. 1
                     ). These Ln-MOFs (Ln = Ce, Gd, Ho) were facilely synthesized using benzenedicarboxylic acid (BDC) as ligand and characterized to be nanosheets. They were tested in NaIO4-H2O2 system and exhibited excellently enhanced-CL emission. Experimental conditions were optimized to obtain the optimum signals. The CL mechanism was systematically studied and demonstrated that Ln-MOFs catalyzed generation of some reactive oxygen species (ROS) (·O2
                     −, 1O2 and ·OH) on their surfaces and induced the enhanced CL.

In order to explore how ultrasonic wave affected the synthesized MOFs and the CL emissions of Ln-MOFs-NaIO4-H2O2 systems, CL intensities of Ln-MOFs-NaIO4-H2O2 systems were compared between the systems using hydrothermal synthesized and ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs (Fig. 5
                        ). Comparing with the hydrothermal synthesized Ln-MOFs, CL intensities of Ln-MOFs-NaIO4-H2O2 systems were obviously enhanced by ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs. Brunauet-Emmett-Teller (BET) surface areas of both hydrothermal synthesized and ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs were detected (Fig. 6
                        ) and the results explained the above difference. BET surface area of hydrothermal synthesized Ce-MOFs, Gd-MOFs and Ho-MOFs were 1.260, 3.693 and 3.574 m2 g−1, respectively, while that of ultrasonic synthesized Ce-MOFs, Gd-MOFs and Ho-MOFs were 22.589, 53.151 and 31.986 m2 g−1, respectively. Pore size distribution curves of both hydrothermal synthesized and ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs also were supplied in Fig. S5. Most of the pores distributed in hydrothermal synthesized Ln-MOFs kept the sizes of 3–4 nm while those distributed in ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs exhibited a variety of sizes. More mesopores in ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs resulted in more structural defects [24] which were benefical for catalyzing CL reactions. The larger surface areas and more structural defects of ultrasonic synthesized Ln-MOFs gave promise for the stronger CL emissions.
